2026-02-23 20:56:43,772 - INFO - Description: , Loch Katrine, Stronachlachar, Scotland, United Kingdom, UK
On a late winter afternoon, a heavy mist hangs over the hills surrounding Loch Katrine in Stronachlachar, Scotland. The muted colours of the February landscape are dominated by dark evergreen forests and the bare branches of deciduous trees.

Nestled on the shore is a utility building, part of the infrastructure for the Loch Katrine aqueduct scheme. In the background, large electricity pylons march across the rugged terrain, their forms softened by the thick fog.

This scene captures the intersection of nature and industry in the Scottish Highlands. Since its inauguration by Queen Victoria in 1859, Loch Katrine has served as the primary freshwater reservoir for the city of Glasgow. The structures around the loch are components of this major feat of Victorian engineering, which was built to provide clean water to the city and continues to be a vital part of the region's water supply today.
